{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12251"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12251"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.37,0.51,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-11-14T18:56:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T17:57:25+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-11-23T15:06:29+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 18:45:43"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12251"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"3779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6233"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11627"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44701"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63930"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man is planned to undergo an internal fixation of a fractured humerus, sustained when falling off a trampoline. His pain is under control and he has no other symptoms besides embarrassment. He has recently been diagnosed with hyperparathyroidism after an incidental finding of hypercalcaemia on a routine laboratory examination. Treatment of this has yet to be initiated. On physical examination he is neurovascularly intact distal to the fracture site and his vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis ECG and pre-operative blood tests are unremarkable apart from a serum calcium of 2.9 mmol/L (2.1 - 2.6).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV hydrocortisone","Haemodialysis","Bisphosphonates","0.9% NaCl","Thiazide diuretic"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has asymptomatic hypercalcaemia. Hypercalcaemia is defined as a serum calcium of \u0026gt;2.6mmol/L and most often occurs as a result of either malignancy or primary hyperparathyroidism. Hypercalcaemia is frequently without symptoms, however features of renal stones, lethargy, fatigue, confusion, depression, irritability, constipation, polyuria and polydipsia may occur. Chronic symptoms are more consistent with hyperparathyroidism, whereas more recent onset of symptoms may be more suggestive of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial step in the management of hypercalcaemia is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydration with normal saline (0.9% NaCl\u003C/strong\u003E) which acts to decrease serum calcium concentration by dilution. The increase in extracellular volume also acts to reduce serum calcium concentrations via increased renal calcium clearance. The rate of fluid therapy depends on the degree of hypercalcaemia, severity of dehydration, and the ability of the patient to tolerate rehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary to correct hypercalcaemia in patients with renal failure or whom are non-responsive to fluid therapy and medical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous bisphosphates\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered second line in the management of hypercalcaemia which is non-responsive to fluid therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are thought to be effective in patients with hypercalcaemia secondary to lymphoma, sarcoidosis or other granulomatous causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiazide diuretics \u003C/strong\u003Eare inappropriate in the management of hypercalcaemia and have been linked with increased serum calcium concentrations as an adverse reaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The initial treatment of acute severe hypercalcaemia is rehydration with 0.9% NaCl.","Hypercalcaemia can be asymptomatic but may present with renal stones, lethargy, and other systemic symptoms.","Thiazide diuretics can increase serum calcium levels and are contraindicated in hypercalcaemia."],"references":["Bilezikian JP, Bandeira L, Khan A, Cusano NE. Hyperparathyroidism. Lancet. 2018 Jan 13;391(10116):168-178. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(17)31430-7. Epub 2017 Sep 17. PMID: 28923463. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28923463/","Pokhrel B, Leslie SW, Levine SN. Primary Hyperparathyroidism. [Updated 2024 Mar 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441895/","Walker MD, Silverberg SJ. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2018 Feb;14(2):115-125. doi: 10.1038/nrendo.2017.104. Epub 2017 Sep 8. PMID: 28885621; PMCID: PMC6037987. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28885621/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12251"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T17:57:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T17:57:48+10:30","number":5,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-11T17:57:21+10:30","plagiarismScore":11.5,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4773-5.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T034617Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=c511e4a5e42d378b8690dde1e15ec41d04bc3f5a1c7c7b994d659e6efd233bf6"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78588"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/